To capture a variable by reference, we prepend an ampersand (&) to the variable name in the capture. Unlike variables that are captured by value, variables that are captured by reference are non-const, unless the variable they’re capturing isconst. Capture by reference should be preferred over capture by value whenever you would normally prefer passing an argument to a function by reference (e.g. for non-fundamental types).Here’s the above code withammocaptured by reference:#include <iostream>

int main()
{
  int ammo{ 10 };

  auto shoot{
    // We don't need mutable anymore
    [&ammo]() { // &ammo means ammo is captured by reference
      // Changes to ammo will affect main's ammo
      --ammo;

      std::cout << "Pew! " << ammo << " shot(s) left.\n";
    }
  };

  shoot();

  std::cout << ammo << " shot(s) left\n";

  return 0;
}This produces the expected answer:Pew! 9 shot(s) left.
